japan is a growing consumer of nuts but an 
agriculture department report says american exporters are finding 
the market a bit hard to crack 
the departments foreign agricultural service said that japanese 
imports of tree nuts increased more than 40 percent in five years to 
almost 64000 metric tons worth 220 million in 1987 
although us almonds and walnuts are on the upswing in japan 
some other foreign suppliers are much bigger for certain kinds of 
nuts 
japan has no quotas on the import of tree nuts the report said 
but import duties have ranged from 4 percent for almonds to 9 
percent for pistachios and macadamia nuts 10 percent for hazelnuts 
and 16 percent for chestnuts and walnuts 
however under the usjapan beef and citrus agreement signed 
last july japan agreed to eliminate the duty on pistachios lower 
it for macadamias and pecans to 5 percent and reduce the walnut 
duty to 10 percent the report said 
although the us share of the market for pistachios hazelnuts 
and macadamia nuts are relatively small sales have increased 
notably in the past few years and the future appears bright the 
report said 
iran is the main supplier of pistachios to japan turkey is the 
largest provider of hazelnuts and kenya has more than half of the 
market for macadamia nuts 
