an attractive major new ballet and a brief 
rather insignificant ballet duet both choreographed by peter 
martins were danced for the first time by the new york city ballet 
on thursday night 
mozart serenade for four couples four women soloists and a 
corps de ballet filled the stage in a balanced flowing george 
balanchine way without looking like an imitation of a balanchine 
ballet 
balance is appropriate because the music is selections from 
mozarts serenades in d major however the symmetry is more 
relaxed than rigid giving the dance a contemporary look when one 
of the four lead couples has a duet the other six dancers stand as 
onlookers in two rows of three rather than staying always as couples 
the corps de ballet flowed smoothly melting from three rows of 
dancers which gave soloists aisles to dance in to form a picture 
frame outlining the soloists 
the dancing was of a high order and stressed ensemble with 
soloists and corps presenting one picture the main costume color 
by barbara maters was pearl gray accented attractively by darker 
grays gray draperies were hung at each side of the stage 
the four lead couples mostly relatively new to the company were 
margaret tracey jeffrey edwards roma sosenko michael byars 
zippora karz ben huys marisa cerveris and philip neal 
martins also was in a formal mood for the brief pas de deux 
titled beethoven romance kyra nichols wore green over purple 
chiffon and adam luders costume suggested a viennese cavalry 
officers uniform and boots the dance was romantic the couple 
both dancing beautifully moved away from each other and met again 
in embraces 
miss nichols had a brief solo but there were no solo variations 
for luders he had to be content with dancing away from the 
ballerina and jumping thrusting one leg high and behind him as he 
reached a far corner a step he does very well a viewer was left 
with the feeling that there might have been more 
lamar alsop was the noteworthy soloist in beethovens romance 
in f major for violin and orchestra robert irving conducted 
the evening began with a terrific presentation of interplay 
jerome robbins 1945 witty working of morton goulds music byers 
shone leading the section titled horseplay the finale was 
balanchines exhilarating stars and stripes 
the company is dancing through feb 26 at the new york state 
theater 
