<TEXT>
the american bar associations president says 
there are limits to how much secrecy the lawyers group will give up 
in evaluating nominees for the federal bench but hes willing to 
meet with senators about possible changes in procedure 
the issue of how the aba rates judicial candidates came up again 
thursday in the senate judiciary committee it first arose during 
consideration of unsuccessful supreme court nominees robert h bork 
and douglas h ginsburg and came to a head during hearings on 
anthony kennedy whose nomination was approved 
the supreme court is also considering two challenges to the abas 
confidential role in screening applicants 
it seems especially appropriate that we undertake this 
reevaluation before the committee faces another supreme court 
nomination rather than in the context of that operation which we 
started to do during the kennedy nomination sen charles e 
grassley riowa said thursday 
i believe that we must do it if we are to avoid a repeat of the 
very unsatisfying situation and the hard feelings arising out of the 
bork ginsburg kennedy series of hearings he said 
at best there is uniform discomfort with the way the aba 
proceeds said committee chairman joseph r biden jr reflecting 
the bipartisan nature of the criticism 
biden ddel said that he and ranking republican sen strom 
thurmond rsc will arrange to meet with top leaders of the aba 
and its standing committee on the federal judiciary to try to 
resolve the problems 
during the december 1987 hearings on kennedy some republicans 
called for the aba panel to hold its deliberations on judicial 
candidates in public since the senate gives great weight to its 
advice 
however panel chairman harold r tyler jr refused saying 
you are free to accept or reject our views you are free to ignore 
us 
during the bork hearings sen orrin g hatch rutah accused 
four members of the aba panel of being willing to play politics 
on the nomination while 10 of the 15 panel members gave bork the 
highest rating of well qualified four reportedly said he was 
unqualified and a fifth was said to have taken the neutral ground of 
not opposed 
aba president robert raven reached in denver where the aba is 
holding its midyear meeting said his organization would be happy 
to meet with the judiciary committee 
weve been working for them since 1948 and theyre our bosses 
so to speak raven said were always looking for ways to 
improve the system 
but he said there would be limits on how much secrecy the 
standing committee would give up saying some of that material would 
have to remain confidential due to possible repercussions against 
people who speak to the panel when asked about a judicial nominee 
that person practices in the area of the nominee noted 
raven with the san francisco law firm of morrison amp foerster if 
that person said something critical and the nominee became a judge 
it could cause problems for him 
tyler was not in his new york office on thursday and his 
secretary said he would be unavailable until next week 
the supreme court is considering a consolidated case of two 
challenges to the abas confidential role in screening federal 
judicial candidates a lower court judge ruled that imposing the 
federal advisory committee act which requires public scrutiny of 
advisory groups on judicial selection would violate the 
constitutional doctrine of separation of powers 
biden noted that the aba got involved in the evaluation process 
to keep the appointment of judges from being a political 
cesspool and to make it hard for a president or a senator to 
put a crony on the bench 
he asked committee members to give him comments and criticisms of 
the aba for discussion during his and thurmonds meeting with aba 
representatives 
following that meeting there may be an informal session with the 
entire judiciary committee and if necessary the committee would 
call a formal public hearing biden said 
