federal ethics officials say health and human 
services secretarydesignate louis sullivan appears to have no 
conflict of interest problems but an fbi investigation into his 
tenure as a medical school president continues 
an atlanta lawyer said thursday that his client a suspended 
fulton county ga commissioner convicted of extortion told the 
fbi that sullivan never tried to improperly influence him 
in a halfhour meeting with fbi agents earlier this week 
reginald eaves was asked about his relationship with sullivan 
president of the morehouse school of medicine in atlanta said the 
attorney charles r floyd jr 
morehouse paid eaves more than 34000 as a lecturer over four 
years while eaves used his seat on the county commission to promote 
measures that benefited the school published reports said eaves had 
lectured twice during the time he was paid by the school 
according to floyd eaves told agents that sullivan never 
sought to influence any of the decisions he had to make as a 
commissioner either as a result of his friendship or any other 
position he might have had with morehouse college 
the lawyer also said eaves told the fbi he had not negotiated his 
position with morehouse through sullivan directly and was unsure 
sullivan knew that he was being paid by the school as a lecturer 
sullivan and eaves were undergraduates together at morehouse 
college and their relationship has been primarily of a social 
nature floyd said 
the interview took place at a federal prison at maxwell air force 
base in montgomery ala where eaves is serving a sixyear sentence 
for extortion the lawyer said he is appealing his conviction 
on another front sullivan got a boost from the office of 
government ethics which is working on sullivans request for 
permission to maintain a relationship with the medical school he 
founded while at the same time he heads hhs the possibilities 
include a paid sabbatical 
don campbell deputy director of the office told the associated 
press that the office foresees no problems with that issue 
sullivans finances or any potential conflicts of interest between 
the new job and federal aid to morehouse which in fiscal 1988 
amounted to 58 million from hhs 
its simply a matter now of getting the forms written down 
because all the problems have been worked out campbell said 
the white house has cited the continuing fbi background check and 
the incomplete financial disclosure forms as reasons for asking 
congress to postpone sullivans confirmation hearing it had been 
scheduled for wednesday this week but the senate finance committee 
agreed to put if off indefinitely 
the fbi had no comment 
at morehouse the fbi has been asking school officials about 
sullivans connection to eaves who was found guilty last may of 
accepting 35000 from an undercover fbi agent in exchange for his 
vote on a zoning matter he was suspended from the commission when 
he was indicted in october 1987 
they talked to me about a range of issues about dr sullivans 
fitness for the position of hhs secretary including that eaves 
and many other things said dr james goodman executive vice 
president of the medical school 
he declined to identify the other issues 
one proposal eaves pushed as a commissioner was to increase 
morehouses participation at grady memorial hospital he wanted the 
county hospital authority to allow morehouse to provide more patient 
care at grady 
jw pinkston executive director of grady said that the fbi had 
contacted him and that other hospital administrators in the atlanta 
region have told him they also had been questioned by the fbi in a 
background check on sullivan 
he said the agents asked routine questions which were very 
appropriate 
