<TEXT>
chinese artists held an exhibition friday night to 
raise money for the relatives of jailed dissidents rekindle a 
oncebanned literary magazine and set up a foundation to publish 
controversial political essays 
the artists who live in china and abroad were once members of 
the star group an underground art and political society that 
flourished briefly during a period of relative political freedom 10 
years ago 
the exhibition was held in the apartment of a western european 
diplomat and attended mostly by foreigners and chinese artists 
at least nine of the 25 works of art were sold raising about 
5405 for the group said ren wanding a chinese dissident who was 
jailed from 1979 to 1983 for advocating multiparty democracy all 
the buyers were foreigners 
ren said some of the money will be used to help people whose 
relatives were jailed for political reasons 
amnesty international says thousands of people are in jail in 
china for their beliefs religious political or otherwise 
wei jingsheng an electrician who was active in the 1979 
democracy wall movement and xu wenli a leading figure in the 
prodemocracy april 5 forum are two of the best known political 
prisoners both were sentenced to 15 years in prison in 1979 for 
counterrevolutionary activities 
ren said some money also will go to the rebirth of today 
magazine a periodical of experimental poetry and short stories that 
was published underground from 1979 until it was banned in late 1980 
during its time the organizers of today escaped jail terms 
because the periodical was purely literary and avoided politics bei 
dao a wellknown poet said the new magazine would follow the same 
line 
ren said the remaining money will be used to start a foundation 
to help political thinkers publish essays that cannot find a place 
in the staterun press 
chinas publishing industry including its newspapers and 
magazines are all under state control statepublished books and 
magazines are censored for political material 
recently the country has witnessed a flourishing of illegal 
publishing houses most print pornography or translations of risque 
novels from the west and very few concentrate on politics or other 
intellectual subjects 
over the past 18 months china has allowed debate to flourish on 
the economy and art but talk about political reform has been scant 
several of the star groups artists who have since emigrated 
from china returned to beijing for the exhibition 
wang keping one of chinas most famous sculptors who lives in 
france said he came back to help his own friends 
they wanted money but we artists are poor he said so we 
decided to give them some of our works to help them 
