<TEXT>
news of a secret twoday meeting 
at a west german hotel reveals that after years of baleful silence 
northern ireland politicians are talking again across the communal 
divide 
but the sudden glare of publicity threatens to push them back 
into their trenches 
for warweary northern irelanders the report that dominated 
bbctv news thursday night was electrifying leading catholic and 
protestant politicians had spent two days in a duisburg hotel in 
october working out a proposed formula for jointly governing the 
british province under a form of autonomy known as devolved 
government 
but by friday party leaders from all sides had poured cold water 
on the notion accusing the bbc of overdramatizing its story 
john hume who as leader of the social democratic and labor party 
is the provinces top catholic politician called it nonsense 
ian paisley the hardline protestant leader of the democratic 
unionist party and james molyneaux leader of the official 
unionists the larger more moderate protestant party also denied 
any negotiations had taken place on the form of northern irelands 
future government 
the meeting was arranged by an unidentified german clergyman and 
was attended by paisleys deputy peter robinson jack allen of the 
official unionists austin currie of the mainly catholic sdlp and 
gordon mawhinney deputy leader of the alliance a small strictly 
nonsectarian party it was followed up over the past four months by 
talks in northern ireland 
sinn fein the irish republican armys political wing was not 
invited 
mawhinney insisted friday that despite the poohpoohing from 
party leaders progress was made 
the mere act of talking was significant he said in an interview 
because stalemate has prevailed ever since the signing of the 1985 
angloirish agreement which gave dublin a say in northern irelands 
affairs 
protestant politicians who regard the agreement as a gross 
foreign intrusion into the affairs of their 1 million followers 
have refused to negotiate with the sdlp unless the accord is shelved 
the sdlp having helped midwife the pact on behalf of the 
600000strong catholic minority predictably rejects that condition 
thus for more than three years northern ireland politics has 
amounted to little more than a prolonged sulk leaving the field 
open to the ira and its extremist protestant counterparts since the 
agreement was signed 258 more lives have been lost 
what was different about duisburg in many respects was that the 
parties agreed that instead of us all going home and putting our 
feet up we would see if there was any basis for moving forward 
said mawhinney 
a basis was found he said in a form of words which the 
participants felt they could present to their leaders for further 
discussion 
he said it entailed agreement on devolved government as the best 
way forward and putting the angloirish agreement aside for a fixed 
period while negotiations continued at a higher level 
currie confirmed that he and the three other parties agreed that 
to facilitate dialogue it was worth considering a suspension of 
the main workings of the agreement the periodic meetings between 
british and irish ministers to discuss ulsters affairs 
the angloirish agreement broke the irish logjam by forcing the 
protestants to realize that they had lost their traditional veto 
over any compromise with the catholics 
but it created another logjam downstream said mawhinney 
a key question is whether the irish and british governments 
which signed the agreement are willing to see it put on ice the 
widely held assumption here is that they will go along with anything 
that offers real prospects for peace 
another question is whether the publicity has killed the 
initiative already angry words have been exchanged among the 
participants over who was to blame for the story getting out 
the nature of northern irish politics is that progress can 
only be made behind closed doors and when it comes out into the 
open people tend to scurry back to secure positions said peter 
barry irelands former foreign minister who helped negotiate the 
1985 agreement 
mawhinney said the duisburg parley reflected a new realism 
among northern ireland politicians a willingness to look at the 
other side of the equation to say yes i recognize that you have a 
problem but you must recognize that i have a problem too and how 
can we overcome these problems 
</TEXT>
