<TEXT>
a federal appeals court friday upheld the 
authority of the environmental protection agency to make agreements 
with pesticide manufacturers permitting inventories to be used up 
after federal pesticide licenses are cancelled 
us district court judge louis oberdorfer had enjoined epa from 
permitting velsicol inc the only manufacturer of chlordane and the 
related chemical heptachlor from selling the chemicals under an 
agreement that included cancellation of the companys license 
that september 1987 agreement provided that no more chlordane or 
heptachlor could be sold by velsicol after april 15 1988 epa was 
concerned however that it might not be able to win agreements to 
end the use of other pesticides if oberdorfers decision stood 
the chemicals have been used to drive termites away from the 
foundations of houses epa believes the pesticides pose a high risk 
of cancer to people living in homes treated that way 
oberdorfer held that epa must examine the risks and benefits of 
using up existing stocks epa maintained that it was not required to 
make such an examination because it was clear the agreement with 
velsicol would result in a dramatic reduction in use and less 
risk to the public than any other course of action 
the agency said it could not justify an emergency ban stopping 
all use immediately and in any lesser proceeding to end use the 
manufacturer could continue to produce and sell the chemical 
meaning that more would be introduced into the environment than 
would be the case if inventories were used up under the agreement 
at the time of the agreement inventories were estimated at 
110000 pounds about a two months supply 
</TEXT>
