<TEXT>
in a sex discrimination challenge to the 
scholastic aptitude test a federal judge ruled friday that new york 
state may not use sat scores as the sole criterion in determining 
scholarship winners 
us district judge john walker said it apparently was the first 
case in which female students sought to use federal civil rights 
statutes to challenge a states reliance upon standardized tests 
the evidence is clear that females score significantly below 
males on the sat while they perform equally or slightly better than 
males in high school walker wrote 
the judge said the state education department and its 
commissioner thomas sobol both named in the suit rely solely upon 
the sat in awarding regents and empire scholarships he said that 
practice deprives young women of the opportunity to compete 
equally for these prestigious scholarships 
the judge ordered the state to change its method of awarding the 
scholarships 
state officials said they had no immediate comment on the ruling 
isabelle katz pinzler director of the womens rights project for 
the american civil liberties union and lead attorney for the case 
hailed the decision 
its really a very important precedentsetting case she 
said its really not fair to anybody to give a scholarship based 
on a threehour test given on a saturday afternoon rather than 
basing it upon four years of high school 
stanford vonmayrhauser general counsel for the educational 
testing service of princeton nj the creator of the sat said 
i think it the ruling will have limited application critics of 
the sat will have false comfort if they think the test is doomed 
new york and massachusetts are the only states that give state 
scholarships based solely upon sat scores 
the suit was filed by the aclu on behalf of the new york chapter 
of the national organization for women the girls club of america 
and 10 female students 
