<TEXT>
while critics say he has broadcast dissonant 
signals about the economys health alan greenspan has made it clear 
beyond any misunderstanding that his no 1 fear is inflation 
based on greenspans repeated acknowledgment of that fear and 
his actions in allowing interest rates to rise substantially since 
becoming federal reserve chairman greenspan might appear to be at 
odds with the white house 
is he 
on january 24 greenspan told congress that in his view inflation 
was too high from the fourth quarter of 1987 to the fourth of 1988 
the gross national product deflator a measure of inflation rose 
41 percent compared with 31 percent a year earlier he said it 
might have been even worse were it not for higher interest rates 
the next day president bush stated that his fears of inflation 
were not as acute as those apparently held by greenspan igniting 
rumors of a rift between the fed and the white house 
greenspan denies it stating that such notions are exaggerations 
the white house hasnt declared itself on whether there is a 
disagreement but there are signs that a fundamental one could 
develop 
it lies in differing priorities 
greenspan has a lot of experience with inflation having honed 
his advisory skills during the days of the great and unlamented 
inflation of the 1970s he knows that when it gets a head of steam 
it cant be stopped short of a crash 
in his view that point may be approaching there is evidence 
that labor is beginning to press for more costly benefits if not 
higher wages the jobless rate is down to very low 53 percent and 
perhaps falling still there may be little idle industrial capacity 
that can accommodate further growth 
bushs economic plan is based on economic growth which rising 
interest rates generally obstruct there are many reasons political 
and economic for seeking that growth none is more important than 
this growth means revenues 
nobody needs to be reminded how important higher revenues are for 
reducing a budget deficit which the administration is commanded by 
law to do higher revenues improve your options you dont need cut 
politically popular projects 
higher interest rates can cause a lot more problems for the 
administration if only for the reason that nobody owes more money 
and pays more interest than uncle sam interest costs today are 
about 15 percent of budget outlays 
higher interest rates also impact business development the 
answer to capacity restraints is for industry to expand production 
facilities but will that happen if business fears interest rates 
will continue to climb 
the expansion issue touches on two more important considerations 
the value of the dollar and the trade deficit higher interest rates 
might strengthen the dollar a stronger dollar would hurt us 
exports and might raise imports 
higher interest costs also would add difficulties to an already 
impossibly complex and politically tricky issue that of bailing out 
the failed savings and loan associations as it is this issue is a 
nowin situation anyway 
nobody yet knows for example where the scores of billions of 
dollars needed will come from now consider that just tiny increases 
in interest rates could make that job billions of dollars more 
difficult to manage 
it might be as greenspan indicates that any differences of 
opinion with the white house are exaggerated but the potential is 
there and if only minor differences now exist they could become 
exaggerated by events 
</TEXT>
