<TEXT>
britain is in danger of losing many important art 
works some hanging in hallowed halls for centuries because 
national museums cant match the high prices offered by foreign 
buyers art critics say 
one such work is mappa mundi a 13thcentury world map on vellum 
that is one of the countrys greatest medieval treasures it now is 
held by the hereford cathedral which plans to put it up for auction 
in june because it needs money for extensive building repairs 
some experts say the work could fetch 25 million pounds 44 
million at recent exchange rates 
in 1952 the government set up a safety net in an effort to 
keep important art treasures in britain 
under the plan export licenses are required for objects more 
than 50 years old and in most cases worth more than 16000 pounds 
28000 but if an object is more than 50 years old and also has 
been in britain for 50 years or more a panel of experts is called 
in 
if the experts conclude the item should stay in britain a 
government reviewing committee can delay its export for up to six 
months while museums try to match the buyers price 
works are judged by their aesthetic historic and scholarly 
importance 
one painting that met all three criteria was selfportrait as 
saint matthew by the dutch artist anthony van dyck it had hung in 
england for centuries and went on sale in 1987 the experts 
concluded that its departure would be a great loss to the nation 
but no british museum could match the price of 430000 pounds 
then 785000 offered by a foreigner the painting then was 
shipped to its new owner in zurich switzerland identified only as 
p nathan 
another such setback may be in store this year 
seascape folkestone by the famous landscape painter jmw 
turner 17751851 sold in 1984 to an anonymous private buyer for a 
british record of 73 million pounds 10 million not until 
recently was an export license applied for since no museum has been 
able to match the record price the export license is expected to be 
issued soon 
art critics say the problem derives partly from spiraling market 
prices that have placed some works out of reach of all but the 
gettys of the united states and the japanese the latest rising 
force on the international art market 
but many critics increasingly blame the conservative government 
of prime minster margaret thatcher for failing to help local museums 
keep pace they suggest that government strategies for keeping 
treasures at home arent working 
the rising prices appeal to private collectors faced with high 
inheritance taxes or rising costs of maintaining stately homes 
universities and similar institutions are tempted to sell their art 
collections because of government budget cuts 
the likelihood that the mappa mundi will wind up overseas has 
prompted one member of the house of lords to propose an outright ban 
on exporting some objects 
government officials acknowledge that british rules are among the 
most flexible in europe but they argue that tightening them would 
stifle an export market than brings 21 billion a year to britain 
the system to safeguard this countrys treasures is coming 
dangerously close to being a pointless sham anna somerscocks 
editor of the respected art monthly apollo wrote in a recent 
editorial the collapsing safety net 
it was time she said for the government to decide whether we 
are at all serious about trying to keep great works of art in this 
country 
the export review system created in 1952 endeavored to balance 
the art markets needs with that of the nations art critic kevin 
conru wrote in a survey of the systems used by more than 50 other 
nations 
france he said has a reputation for having arbitrary and 
unpredictable rules which auctioneers believe have inhibited 
trade the netherlands bans entire collections from foreign 
ownership 
nowadays major museums simply cant afford to compete with the 
big foreign buyers the getty museum in malibu calif for 
instance spends more each year on purchases than the combined 
purchasing budgets of britains 13 state museums 
conru and others say the export review system one of the first 
of its kind in the world now is in need of reappraisal 
in 198687 the government reviewing committee considered 26 
objects and delayed the export of 15 eight of them worth a total 
of 26 million stayed in britain the other seven worth 60 
million went abroad 
those that went abroad included old masters drawings from the 
chatsworth stately home whose export was one of the greatest 
artistic losses to this country this century the committee noted 
in the last year 12 objects worth 18 million were saved while 
a dozen worth 14 million went abroad 
sir peter wakefield director of the only private art charity 
helping public collections says the small number of objects 
reviewed indicates something is wrong 
the great bulk of art objects are flowing out without any 
restraint at all he said in an interview 
ms somerscocks says the expert advisers tend to lack vigilance 
knowing that their efforts will be useless since the museums 
lack the money to buy objects back 
museum purchase grants many smaller than the cost of a single 
impressionist painting nowadays have been frozen since 1982 and 
will remain so until 1991 
arts minister richard luce has agreed to review the grant system 
although not necessarily to strengthen it said the governments 
office of arts and libraries 
the money shortage has increased the burden on britains two main 
art funding groups wakefields private national artcollections 
fund and the larger quasigovernmental national heritage memorial 
fund 
the latter created in 1980 has spent more than 100 million 
pounds 175 million saving important art objects 
but art accounts only for a fraction of its work which ranges 
from coastal scenery to endangered butterflies and stately homes 
brian morris a fund trustee says the fund so far has not failed 
to save an important object from being exported 
but this year he said in an interview if things go on 
increasing in price and number as they have then the collision 
course between demand and lack of funds is likely to come 
lord blake chairman of the royal commission on historical 
manuscripts has called for a ban on exporting objects like the 
mappa mundi but doubts it will happen 
memorial fund chairman lord charteris opposes a ban 
one of the beauties of london is that its the center of the 
art trade and i wouldnt want that changed he said still im 
worried about the future 
</TEXT>
