<TEXT>
for more than 10 years general motors 
corps sprawling assembly plant here has been lurching and stalling 
like an old duster 
so frequent have been the layoffs and startups union officials 
said thursday that many of the 2100 workers are skeptical about 
gms announcement that the plant will shut down indefinitely in 
august 
theyre still in a waitandsee mode said arthur t grniet 
a 24year veteran of the plant because there have been so many 
layoffs the perception in everyones mind is that ill get called 
back 
but gm officials and industry analysts threw cold water on that 
perception thursday 
id say the chances of that plant reopening are very low 
because gm still has too much production capacity said douglas 
laughlin who follows the automaker for the wall street investment 
firm bear stearns amp co 
the plant built in 1948 assembles two of gms abody cars the 
oldsmobile cutlass ciera and buick century it was hit by temporary 
shutdowns ranging from a few weeks to several months in 1977 
1981 1982 and 1987 
adding to workers optimism that this shutdown too will prove 
to be temporary was the wording of gms announcement the automaker 
said it would idle the plant for an indefinite period rather 
than shut it down permanently 
but that wording in fact was dictated largely by the companys 
contract with the united auto workers which prevents it from 
permanently shutting most factories 
gm spokesman dee allen sought thursday to underline that the 
coming shutdown differs fundamentally from earlier ones 
the real difference is that in the past when the plant has had 
to be shut down or a shift taken off its been because of a 
temporary volume related adjustment he said 
this time allen said gm has decided to reduce its productive 
overcapacity and bring down costs by building acars only at its 
plants in st therese quebec oklahoma city okla and ramos 
aripze mexico 
those plants which already build acars can easily meet the 
demand for the olds cutlass buick century and other models in 1990 
and beyond he said 
what that means is we dont have a product to build in 
framingham anymore thats very different from the simple volume 
adjustments that weve had to make in the past allen said 
philip b ernst chairman of framinghams board of selectmen 
said thursday he was optimistic gm would eventually decide to build 
some other models in framingham but allen was skeptical about that 
too 
it isnt as if there is a shelf with a lot of products and all 
you have to do is get someone to give you one he said there 
arent those products out there 
the plants high point in recent years came in august 1987 when 
gm invested 240 million in a new paint shop 
until this weeks announcement the low point was in november 
1987 when the plant shut down indefinitely laying off 3700 
workers it reopened last may with the current 2100 employees more 
than half of whom have 20 years or more of service 
allen refused to explain why gm chose to close the framingham 
operation rather than one of the other three acar plants 
each facility has certain advantages and disadvantages some 
are material some are physical some have to do with human factors 
you have to weigh all of those things when you make one of these 
decisions he said gm is not going to discuss the specific 
reasons behind its evaluation of a facility 
</TEXT>
