<TEXT>
the investigation into alleged fraud at the 
nations major futures markets may have doomed the timehonored and 
lucrative practice of dual trading on at least one of the exchanges 
a newspaper reported today 
the chicago tribune quoted unidentified sources as saying chicago 
board of trade officials are drafting a plan that would force 
traders to trade either for themselves or customers but not both 
on a given day 
dual trading under which a trader buys or sells futures 
contracts for himself and for customers has come under attack as a 
potential conflict of interest 
one complaint against the practice is that it creates a situation 
which allows a trader who has a customer order for a large 
transaction to first trade his own account in a way that would 
profit from price swings resulting from filing the customers order 
this practice would violate the current law 
the board of trade and the chicago mercantile exchange both 
permit dual trading however some traders who fill orders for 
brokerage houses are prohibited by the firms from trading their own 
accounts 
brokers and traders at both the merc and the board of trade have 
been under investigation for two years by federal agents who suspect 
customers may have been defrauded of millions of dollars 
in addition to restrictions on dual trading the board of trade 
officials also are expected to propose a deadline for bringing large 
orders to the trading pits the tribune said 
as it is now large orders sometimes show up just seconds before 
closing creating frantic buying and selling as well as completion 
of deals after the closing bell has sounded 
the tribune said the board of trade is expected to announce these 
and other proposed reforms next week 
meanwhile at the merc richard lowrance resigned from the 
exchanges 24member board of governors 
the exchange said thursday that the resignation was for personal 
reasons 
the resignation was not related to the continuing federal 
investigation of suspected trading fraud said merc spokesman andrew 
yemma 
in washington the chairman of the house agriculture committee 
said thursday that congress could reauthorize the commodity futures 
trading commission more quickly if the fbi would share findings from 
its tradingfraud investigation in chicago 
were not asking to be part of the criminal investigation 
said rep e kika de la garza dtexas all we want is 
information that will help us do our job 
the cftcs authority to regulate the nations commodity markets 
expires this year and lawmakers expected fast action on legislation 
to reauthorize the commission through 1994 de la garza said 
thursday 
their plans were altered by disclosure of the fbis undercover 
investigation of the futures markets 
de la garza said he contacted the fbi once the probe was 
disclosed several weeks ago seeking information that would help in 
the committees review of the cftc reauthorization 
we havent seen a thing he said zilch at this time 
the fbi had no immediate comment 
