<TEXT>
investors in the securities markets will have a 
special interest in the budget proposal president bush makes to 
congress this week 
of course anyone with a stake in stocks and bonds will be eager 
to see what the new administration and the legislators can do to 
deal with the governments deficit problems 
but beyond that bushs message scheduled to be delivered 
thursday is expected to contain a proposal dear to the hearts of 
many wall streeters restoring a tax break for longterm capital 
gains 
before passage of the tax reform act of 1986 the maximum tax 
rate on capital gains from the sale of stocks bonds and other 
assets held for more than six months was 20 percent while other 
types of income fell into tax brackets as high as 50 percent 
tax reform lumped all income including capital gains into a 
single category with a maximum tax rate that now stands at 33 
percent 
bush has said he would like to cut the top rate on longterm 
gains to 15 percent 
such a change would seem to go against the spirit of the nations 
new tax system in addition preferential treatment of capital gains 
has long been opposed by some members of congress and others who say 
its benefits go disproportionately to the wealthy 
yet many observers believe bushs idea will get serious 
consideration i think theres a very good chance it or 
something like it will be enacted said wallace head a tax expert 
at the accounting firm of arthur andersen amp co 
the present tax system provides no incentive for longterm 
investment head observed and thats not what we should do 
the tax law now defines long term as more than one year 
between the date of purchase and sale a single maximum rate could 
be established for assets held that long 
alternatively capital gains rates could be set on a sliding 
scale declining as the holding period for an investment increases 
proponents of a break for longterm gains say it would help 
maintain a stable base of capital for business and perhaps 
discourage the kind of shortterm rollofthedice trading that 
contributes to market volatility 
of course given the problem of the budget deficit this is not a 
likely time for politicians to be handing out new tax breaks 
before any change is made in the tax system these days a 
persuasive case must be made that the new setup will add to tax 
receipts or at minimum be revenue neutral 
in the current discussion head acknowledges people will 
allege that the wealthy are getting something so they ought to give 
something back 
advocates of lower capital gains rates insist however that they 
actually increase revenues to the treasury by encouraging more 
people to pursue and realize longterm gains 
it is even possible analysts say that the talk generated by 
bushs proposal has contributed to the improved mood of the stock 
market in recent weeks 
the prospect of a change in the rules has begun to carry some 
weight in the investment decisions people make 
for anyone planning to sell an investment or other property in 
the next year or two the debate certainly bears watching 
