<TEXT>
japans massive current account surplus shrank in 
1988 for the first time in seven years but progress toward reducing 
it petered out at the end of the year a government report showed 
friday 
the finance ministrys report showed that japan continues to 
export far more than it imports and no end to the imbalance is in 
sight 
the current account surplus fell 87 percent to 795 billion 
from 87 billion in 1987 the ministry said in december the 
surplus shrank to 927 billion from 944 billion a year earlier 
but the december surplus was sharply higher than november 1988s 
676 billion the ministry said 
the current account is the broadest measure of a nations 
international financial flows and includes trade investment 
income tourism and other transactions 
japans trade surplus also declined 17 percent during the year 
to 948 billion from 964 billion the previous year it was the 
first annual drop in the trade surplus in six years ministry 
officials said 
but decembers trade surplus continued a recent upward trend 
rising to a record 109 billion from 996 billion a year earlier 
and 756 billion in november 1988 
the ministry announcement did not include breakdowns of trade 
figures by country or region 
the decline in the current account surplus was due primarily to 
the growing number of japanese traveling overseas and increasing 
payments of patent royalties ministry officials said 
a record 840 million japanese travelers spent a record 158 
billion abroad in 1988 compared to the previous years 866 
billion they said 
the yeartoyear drop in the current account surplus during 
december came as a relief to the government which had expressed 
concern when the gap grew for two months in a row in october and 
november 
the recent increases in the surplus raised the prospect that the 
governments attempt to restore balance to its external accounts may 
have begun faltering after months of steady declines resulting 
partly from the appreciation of the japanese yen 
the drop in the current account surplus in 1988 does not 
necessarily give reason for optimism according to finance ministry 
officials we cant say whether the downtrend is going to 
continue one ministry official said it depends on a lot of 
things like oil prices 
a rise in oil prices would increase japans import bills and 
result in a reduction in the current account surplus 
exports and imports last year as measured when contracts were 
settled were at record highs with exports reaching 2596 billion 
surpassing the previous record of 2246 billion in 1987 imports 
came to 1648 billion far more than the prior record of 1296 
billion in 1981 
japan includes freight and insurance costs in its import figures 
but not in its exports that method makes imports look bigger and 
thus makes the trade surplus appear smaller 
the 1988 statistics showed that vigorous domestic demand in japan 
has pushed up imports finance ministry officials said oil prices 
drifted down most of the year but strong domestic demand for 
manufactured goods led to an increase in imports and helped reduce 
external surpluses they said 
december was the third consecutive month in which japans trade 
surplus showed an increase in addition the surplus was a record 
high exceeding the previous record of 102 billion set in december 
1986 
confounding predictions the record monthly surplus came at a 
time when the yen was at one of its highest points against the us 
dollar making japanese products more expensive overseas since 
then the dollar has rebounded against the yen possibly leading to 
further increases in japanese exports in coming months 
the decrease in the current account surplus in 1988 was the first 
since the account began showing a surplus in 1981 ministry 
officials said 
