<DOCNO> AP890203-0247 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
when youre looking for signs of inflation as 
everyone seems to be these days youll find them there are always 
little pimples that have the potential to become open sores 
the jobless figures are one of them 
unemployment is now down to 52 percent of the labor force a 
level that many economists feel is scraping the bottom of the 
barrel it is after all less than half the unemployment rate at 
which the current expansion began 
when you scrape bottom you tend to get inferior workers they 
have fewer skills and probably none at all they require expensive 
training and even then tend to perform poorly they are costly 
such a situation puts pressure on profits and according to 
inflation theorists causes employers to raise prices thus an 
inflationary spiral is begun 
but is there an alternative to that thesis thats just one of 
the questions being asked by a small number of economists who are 
questioning a lot of the conventional thinking of late 
one of those challenges to convention is that a labor shortgage 
rather than forcing up prices will finally force some industries to 
do without additional labor and instead institute more efficient 
procedures 
some of those industries it is argued have had it too good in 
some of the retail service industries for example employers have 
been able to tap a huge supply of unskilled workers and homemakers 
seeking parttime jobs 
tremendous numbers of workers have been hired by fastfood 
outlets for example because there was an available supply of 
teenagers and adult women seeking parttime jobs it was easier to 
hire than to improve efficiency 
edward yardeni prudentialbache economist observes that from 
1968 to 1988 when payroll employment rose by 38 million 
serviceproducing jobs accounted for an astounding 95 percent of the 
total gain 
these employers are now facing a critical situation do they seek 
to hire more workers from a smaller labor supply and pay them 
everhigher wages or will they be forced to reconsider the 
situation and take another course 
giving urgency to that consideration is another factor many 
service companies are facing a profits squeeze because of consumer 
resistance to higher prices if puts them in the position of being 
unable to tolerate higher costs 
looking for a solution to the problem many companies might be 
forced to reconsider their labor policies they might seek instead 
to obtain higher productivity through better systems for producing 
and delivering products 
there is nothing new in this and it might have been forced on 
service companies long ago were it not for the availability of 
lowcost labor but now that pool may be drying up and no matter 
it is getting more costly 
if this occurs says yardeni and likethinkers then low jobless 
rates in effect will boost national productivity which should 
reduce inflationary pressures 
during the 1970s we experienced high unemployment and high 
inflation in the 1990s we should experience low unemployment and 
low inflation he says 
it is something to think about when you hear the inflation 
alarmists shouting their equivalent of fire they have been at 
it for several years now and one day they might be right 
but as yardeni and others remind us inflation is not an 
inevitable and automatic response to any uncomfortable news 
sometimes we put the proper salve on the pimple sometimes inflation 
doesnt happen 
</TEXT>
