<TEXT>
being a savings and loan customer in texas means 
never being able to say its over 
so far the four sampls and one bank with which ive done business 
have gone through six bailouts buyouts or failures all of them 
have changed names a few twice one branch is now a frozen yogurt 
store with a driveup window 
the tally so far ive lost money only once 
like most people in texas these days my interest in the savings 
and loan crisis goes beyond a casual interest in reading about 
debates in washington to a gut issue whats it mean for me 
in texas the crisis is part of daily conversation 
how do i make the check out now i ask another one of 
those letters came today my wife tells me maybe thats the end 
of it i say hopefully 
not so far 
letters telling us that our accounts had new owners and 
reassuring us that all was well became so frequent that we treated 
them like junk mail 
now i wish i had saved them to show my daughter shell never 
understand why people joke that when you buy a toaster these days 
you get a sampl for free 
i even believe theres a strange sort of charm in driving up to a 
financial institution that has a giant plastic banner across the 
front hiding any sign of its failed past 
one day i pulled up to first texas savings association and saw a 
red sign telling customers the thrift would be closed for four days 
that must be it i thought the end had come 
wrong first texas was closing for the veterans day holiday 
later after it was announced that new york financier ronald o 
perelman had bought the insolvent first texas it had now changed 
names twice in a week i asked a teller how to make out the check 
she had to ask someone 
first texas by the way used to boast we have ways to beat 
the 80s call me a cynic but i think the 80s won 
my wife and i opened a money market account at a somewhat 
notoriously highflying sampl which was paying high rates but had 
already been taken over by the regulators 
maybe thats the end of trouble there we thought not so lamar 
savings was declared insolvent and sold under the southwest plan 
and we got another letter 
we financed a mortgage at an sampl that had already had action 
taken against it by regulators that should be stable we thought 
three days before christmas it was sold to an investor from 
phoenix now we joke about how to make out the mortgage check 
my only loss came from a small investment in an interfirst bank 
bond interfirst was once the largest bank in texas but it was 
crushed by the oil and real estate collapse republicbank another 
texas giant bought interfirst and my bond became a firstrepublic 
bond 
that wasnt so bad until firstrepublic failed too it was 
bought by north carolina national bank 
that wasnt so bad until ncnb decided it wasnt going to be so 
charitable this time the bondholders were wiped out and i was left 
with nothing but a little more wisdom and a loss to declare on my 
taxes 
and probably another piece of junk mail 
</TEXT>
