<TEXT>
federal authorities are increasing their pressure 
on traders and brokers in an effort to win cooperation in their 
investigation of fraud in the worlds two largest commodities 
exchanges sources said friday 
the us attorneys office in chicago has shown some futures 
traders evidence of at least one type of trading offense and has 
invited them to share information in exchange for immunity from 
prosecution reduced charges or a recommendation for a lenient 
sentence say attorneys for some of those subpoenaed over the past 
two weeks 
the pressure increasingly applied being to selected traders and 
brokers is helping to sharpen the focus of the governments twoyear 
undercover investigation of the chicago board of the trade and the 
chicago mercantile exchange the lawyers said 
it tells me they need cooperation said john troelstrup an 
attorney with a number of clients who have been contacted by the 
us attorneys office 
it tells me that the eerie feeling that theyre not focusing on 
anything more than a routine tradepractices investigation may be on 
the mark he said 
anton valukas the us attorney for the northern district of 
illinois has refused to confirm the existence of the investigation 
which was disclosed by the chicago tribune on jan 19 speculation 
about the purpose of the probe has ranged from rooting out trading 
fraud to documenting the laundering of drug money 
defense lawyers said federal prosecutors have shown some traders 
evidence of bag trading in the illegal technique a floor 
broker conspires with another trader the bag man to sell a 
customers futures contract at the low end of an official price 
range and to buy it back for a different customer at the high end of 
the range 
the transaction produces a profit for the bag man which he 
splits with his trading 
futures are binding contracts for delivery of a commodity at a 
specified price on a specified date producers and consumers of 
commodities use the futures markets to lock in prices in advance 
while speculators use them to bet on price movements 
prosecutors also have told some brokers or their attorneys they 
were prepared to accept proffer letters from people under 
investigation defense attorneys said 
in a proffer letter a potential defendant lays out the 
information he is willing to provide in exchange for immunity a 
lesser charge or prosecutors recommendation for leniency if no 
such deal is struck prosecutors agree not to use the information to 
prosecute the individual 
one lawyer who spoke on condition of anonymity said proffer 
letters were fairly routine in criminal investigations 
but troelstrup said it was unusual for federal authorities to let 
it be known publicly albeit through unofficial channels that they 
were willing to negotiate plea bargains 
the government also is seeking handwriting samples from some of 
those subpoenaed by asking them to write down the tradingbadge 
numbers of certain other traders at the chicago mercantile exchange 
defense lawyers said 
troelstrup said federal authorities may want to compare the 
handwriting samples with the handwriting on trading cards obtained 
by subpoena futures traders record on trading cards the price 
quantity time and badge number of the opposing buyer or seller for 
each trade they make 
meanwhile the chicago tribune reported friday that chicago board 
of trade officials were drafting a document that would prohibit 
floor brokers from trading both for their own accounts and on behalf 
of customers dual trading which is unique to futures markets has 
been criticized as inviting trading abuse 
board of trade spokesman michael oconnell would not confirm the 
report saying only that dual trading was one of the issues being 
examined by an internal committee formed earlier this week to make 
recommendations to the exchanges board of directors 
in a statement unrelated to the investigation the chicago merc 
said friday it had fined timothy s fox a trader in the standard amp 
poors 500 stockindex futures pit 50000 for making prearranged 
trades 
</TEXT>
