public service co of new hampshire 
disclosed friday it has agreed to pay 2 million to four former 
owners of the seabrook nuclear power plant so that they wont sue 
the utility over its management of the stalled project 
the agreement is part of a deal under which public service which 
sought bankruptcy protection a year ago because of its 36 percent 
seabrook share would assume 30 million in plant payments being 
skipped by the owner of the fourthlargest share massachusetts 
municipal wholesale electric co 
in return for making mmwecs payments which would keep the 
project afloat through may 1990 public service wanted all present 
and former seabrook owners to agree not to sue it public service 
denies mismanaging the project but says it wants to avoid expensive 
litigation over it 
central maine power co which formerly owned 6 percent of 
seabrook and initially refused to waive its right to sue public 
service now has signed on 
but vermont electric cooperative new hampshire electric 
cooperative and hudson power amp light co of massachusetts which 
own a total of about 4 percent of seabrook wont go along public 
service spokesman nicholas ashooh confirmed friday 
public services bankruptcy judge james yacos must approve the 
agreement for assuming the mmwec payments and the utility on friday 
told him how it got central maine and the other former owners to 
sign on 
