<TEXT>
nissan motor corps american arm will 
distribute 605600 in back pay to settle a race and age bias case 
involving 92 workers in agreement announced friday 
the settlement ends an investigation begun in 1984 to determine 
if nissan usa violated laws against racial and age discrimination 
at its headquarters and regional distribution and sales offices 
the agreement was announced jointly by the equal employment 
opportunity commission in washington and nissan in california 
this agreement is significant because nissan has committed to 
providing increased opportunities in highlevel sales and management 
positions for blacks hispanics women and persons covered by age 
discrimination laws eeoc chairman clarence thomas said 
the eeoc said the back pay would be distributed among 92 blacks 
hispanics women and nissan employees over 40 years old covered by 
the agencys investigation 
ronald cabibi nissan usas vice president of human resources 
and administration said the company denies violating the laws in 
question 
while we believe we have always upheld the principles espoused 
by the eeoc we also recognized there was room for improvement in 
the way we developed opportunities for protected employees and in 
that regard we are specifically committed to implementing several 
changes in our practices a nissan statement said 
nissan usa the american marketing arm of the japanese 
carmaker has headquarters in carson calif 
nissan also agreed to revise recruitment and hiring procedures to 
ensure nondiscriminatory treatment of potential employees eliminate 
college degree requirements for most sales and management positions 
conduct annual training for management on antidiscrimination laws 
and submit compliance reports to the eeoc 
</TEXT>
